<body>

<h1>@HI{{hou ga ii}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vta{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hou ga ii}}}}
<li> @Vnai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{hou ga ii}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{hou ga ii}}}} is used to make a suggestion or to give advice. This construction may come across
as though the speaker is imposing his opinion on the listener, and so it should be used with care.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{every^day carry^move}}shita @EM{{hou ga ii}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is good to exercise every day.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{hou ga ii}}}} is preceded by a verb in the plain negative it means "had better not do".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{heat}}ga arundesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{jaa, ofuroni @KJ{{enter}}ranai @EM{{hou ga ii}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: I have a fever.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: So you'd better not take a bath.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{hou ga ii}}}} implies a choice between two alternatives, even if one is only implied. If a simple
suggestion is being made then @HI{{tara ii}} should be used instead.
</p>

<p>
It is possible to use @Vru{{}} @HI{{@EM{{hou ga ii}}}}, in which case the suggestion is slightly less strong.
However, it is not possible to use the negative past form instead of @Vnai{{}}.
</p>

